    "slug": "talking-to-kids-about-internet-safety",
    "title": "How to Talk to Your Children About Internet Safety Without Them Switching Off",
    "date": "April 1, 2026",
    "readTime": 7,
    "category": "Parent Guidance",
    "excerpt": "Most conversations about internet safety fall flat. Here is how to make them stick and why starting earlier than you think is the key.",
    "metaDescription": "How to talk to your kids about internet safety at every age. Practical conversation starters, what to say, and how to keep the door open.",
    "content": "<p>Most parents know they should be talking to their children about internet safety. Far fewer feel confident doing it well. The conversations tend to fall flat because children roll their eyes, or parents make the internet sound so dangerous that children stop sharing anything at all.</p><h2>What These Conversations Are Not For</h2><p>They are not for reciting a list of rules. They are not for frightening children. And they are definitely not one-off events. The goal is to build the kind of relationship where, when something goes wrong online, your child comes to you.</p><h2>The Most Important Thing You Can Say</h2><p>You will not be in trouble. Those four words matter more than anything else. Because the moment your child encounters something harmful online, their first thought will be whether they will get in trouble for telling you. If they believe the answer is yes, they will handle it alone, often for months.</p><h2>How to Make the Conversations Less Awkward</h2><p><strong>Use news stories.</strong> Ask what they would do if that happened to them. This takes the spotlight off your child and makes it feel hypothetical.</p><p><strong>Bring it up naturally.</strong> If you are watching TV where a character receives a strange message, use that moment. The best conversations happen in the cracks, not in formal settings.</p><p><strong>Ask questions more than you give instructions.</strong> Questions invite children to think. Instructions invite them to nod and forget.</p><h2>Specific Conversations by Age</h2><p><strong>Ages 5-7:</strong> If something makes you feel scared or confused online, tell me. We do not share our home address or school name online.</p><p><strong>Ages 8-11:</strong> Anything you post can be seen by people you did not intend. Being unkind online still counts as being unkind. If someone makes you uncomfortable online, just tell me.</p><p><strong>Ages 12-16:</strong> Once something is sent you cannot control where it goes. People online are not always who they say they are. Grooming can look like someone being very kind and interested in your life.</p><div style=\"background:#F0FDF4;border:2px solid #0EA5A0;border-radius:12px;padding:24px 28px;margin:40px 0;\"><h3 style=\"color:#0B1F3A;margin-top:0;\">Shield Protect Your Family With Our Online Safety Courses</h3><p style=\"color:#374151;\">Our <strong>Family Anchor</strong> course gives you the knowledge and language to talk to your children about online safety at every age.</p><p style=\"color:#374151;margin-bottom:0;\"><a href=\"/courses\" style=\"color:#0EA5A0;font-weight:600;\">Explore Our Courses</a></p></div>"
